Cosatu and Saftu are protesting against corruption, unemployment and the handling of the economy. Aviwe Mtila speaks with Nupsaw regional secretary Neo Mashike. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Cosatu says it won't allow government to use COVID-19 as an excuse not to pay frontline workers. The country's largest trade union federations have joined forces on Wednesday to protest against corruption, unemployment and the handling of the economy. Cosatu and Saftu warned the strike would disrupt government services, transport and schools. READ: Unions embark on mass action Crowds have taken to the streets in a visible show of protest, although the federations urged members to stay at home to minimise the risk of contracting COVID-19. Not all unions participating in the mass action agree with the stay-away principle touted by Cosatu ahead of the demonstration. National Union of Public Service and Allied Workers regional secretary Neo Mashike said, "as Saftu we said, we are coming outside. We're going to show them that as much as we have masses, we are serious about the issues of workers." Cosatu and Saftu are protesting against corruption, unemployment and the handling of the economy. Crowds were addressed outside the Cape Town Civic Centre by union representatives. Courtesy of #DStv403 Cosatu provincial chairperson Motlatsi Tsubane addressed gathered crowds at the Civic Centre in Cape Town before handing over a memorandum of grievances to a representative of the city. READ: PSA speaks out against job losses, corruption The march will proceed to the Western Cape legislature and Parliament. The countries largest trade union federations are joining forces on Wednesday in a nationally coordinated protest. Courtesy of #DStv403 Doctors protesting outside Chris Hani Baragwanath Hospital said the decision to renegue on the 2018 Public Service Salary Adjustment agreement as well as their experiences of being denied PPE and safe working conditions were the final straw.